Nexo OS Kernel Documentation
STM Trace Policy Configuration Interface
📁 /config/stp-policy

Date: June 2015
Kernel Version: 4.3

Description

This directory contains policies that define master and channel allocation rules for software sources that transmit trace data through an STM (System Trace Macrocell) device.

These policies control how trace resources are assigned and isolated across consumers.

📁 Policy Directory
/config/stp-policy/<device>.<policy>

Date: June 2015
Kernel Version: 4.3

Description

This directory is the root of a single STM allocation policy.

The name is composed of:

<device>: STM device name
<policy>: arbitrary policy identifier string
Creation Rules

When creating this directory:

If <device> does not match an existing STM device → ENODEV
If the device already has an active policy → EBUSY
📁 Device Binding (Read-only)
/config/stp-policy/<device>.<policy>/device
Description

Read-only file that indicates the STM device associated with this policy.

Always identical to the <device> portion of the parent directory name
Cannot be modified
📁 Policy Node
/config/stp-policy/<device>.<policy>/<node>
Description

A policy node is a string identifier used by software clients to request allocation of STM trace resources.

It represents a logical consumer of:

masters
channels
📁 Masters Allocation Range
/config/stp-policy/<device>.<policy>/<node>/masters
Description

Defines the range of STM masters available to this node.

Format
<first_master> <last_master>
Behavior
Allocation is restricted to the specified range
Used to enforce isolation between different trace consumers
📁 Channels Allocation Range
/config/stp-policy/<device>.<policy>/<node>/channels
Description

Defines the range of STM channels available to this node.

Format
<first_channel> <last_channel>
Behavior
Limits channel allocation scope
Prevents overlap between independent policy nodes
🧠 Design Notes (Nexo OS)
Policies define strict resource partitioning rules
Allocation is deterministic and range-based
Invalid configuration is rejected at creation time (no fallback behavior)
